The article discusses the disagreement with a district court's decision to impose a nationwide injunction against the President's policy on immigration without allowing the government to provide a written defense. It argues that a single judge should not be able to thwart the President's policy judgment when Congress has given the President authority in this matter. It cites Section 212(f) of the Immigration and Nationality Act, which grants the President the power to impose restrictions on the entry of aliens if it is deemed detrimental to the interests of the United States. The article also mentions the strain on the healthcare system caused by subsidizing uncompensated care for those seeking admission and states that the Administration will vigorously defend the President's policies to protect the interests of the American people.